Definition 2.16. Let $\{X_{c}\}_{c\in\operatorname{Col}}$ and $\{Y_{c}\}_{c\in\operatorname{Col}}$ be two collection of objects in $\mathsf{C}$. The colored $\mathbb{N}$-sequence $\underline{\operatorname{Hom}}_{\{X_{c}\},\{Y_{c}\}}$ is defined by $\underline{\operatorname{Hom}}_{\{X_{c}\},\{Y_{c}\}}(c_{1},\ldots,c_{n};c)=% \underline{\operatorname{Hom}}_{\mathsf{C}}(X_{c_{1}}\otimes\ldots\otimes X_{c% _{n}},Y_{c})$ It has the natural structure of a left module over $\underline{\operatorname{End}}_{\{X_{c}\}}$ and a right module over $\underline{\operatorname{End}}_{\{Y_{c}\}}$ given by compositions.
Definition 7.1. An operad $\mathcal{P}$ is called Hopf if it is equipped with a coassociative diagonal $\Delta_{\mathcal{P}}\colon\thinspace\mathcal{P}\to\mathcal{P}\boxtimes\mathcal% {P}$.
Definition 2.11. For an operadic pair $(\mathcal{P},\mathcal{M})$, an object of $\operatorname{Alg}(\mathcal{P},\mathcal{M})$ is just a $\mathcal{P}$-algebra. For two such objects $A$ and $B$, with structure maps $\chi_{A}:\mathcal{P}\to\underline{\operatorname{End}}_{A}$ and $\chi_{B}:\mathcal{P}\to\underline{\operatorname{End}}_{B}$, a morphism $f$ in $\operatorname{Alg}(\mathcal{P},\mathcal{M})$ is given by a structure map of $\mathcal{P}$-bimodules $\chi_{f}:\mathcal{M}\to\underline{\operatorname{Hom}}_{A,B}$. The composition is induced by $c$ and the identity morphisms are incduced by $\epsilon$.
Definition 4.4. A nice $n$-expression is an expression $s=s_{l}][s_{l+1}]\ldots[s_{k}]|[s_{0}]\ldots[s_{l-1}]$ where • (the absence of the opening bracket for $s_{l}$ is not a typo) • every stretch $s_{i}$ is a nonempty subset of $\{0,1,\ldots,n\}$ • for every $i$, $\max s_{i}=\min s_{i+1}$ • $|s_{i}|\geq 2$ if $i\neq l$ ($|s_{l}|=1$ is allowed) • $\min s_{0}=0$ and $\max s_{k}=n$ • in the case $l=0$ $s_{0}$ is placed to the left of the bar
Definition 7.6. For $F_{1}$ and $F_{2}$ faces either of $I^{n}$ or of $\mathcal{F}(n)$, we say $F_{1}\leq F_{2}$ if $\max F_{1}\leq\min F_{2}$.
Definition 2.20. A short forest is a sequence of planar trees of depth 2. Inner edges are called branches and outer edges are called leaves. For a short forest $F$, let $l(F)$ be the number of leaves, let $b(F)$ be the number of branches and let $t(F)$ be the number of trees.
Definition 4.2. The variety $\mathcal{V}_{\mathbb{T}}$ associated to a finitary monad $\mathbb{T}$ on $\mathsf{Pos}$ has the signature $\Sigma_{\Gamma}=|T\Gamma|\qquad\text{for every $\Gamma\in\mathsf{Pos}_{\mathsf% {f}}$}.$ That is, operations of arity $\Gamma$ are elements of the poset $T\Gamma$. For each $\Gamma$, we impose inequations of the following two types: (1) $\Gamma\vdash\sigma\leq\tau$ for all $\sigma\leq\tau$ in $T\Gamma$ (with operations used as terms as per 3.10), and (2) $\Gamma\vdash k^{*}(\sigma)=\sigma(k)$ for all $\Delta\in\mathsf{Pos}_{\mathsf{f}}$, monotone $k\colon\Delta\rightarrow T\Gamma$ and $\sigma\in T\Delta$.
Definition 3.12. Let $A$ be a $\Sigma$-algebra. Given a context $\Gamma$ (of variables) and a monotone interpretation $f\colon\Gamma\to A$, the evaluation map is the partial map $f^{\#}\colon\mathscr{T}(\Gamma)\to|A|$ defined recursively by (1) $f^{\#}(x)=f(x)$ for every $x\in|\Gamma|$, and (2) $f^{\#}(\sigma(g))$ is defined for $\sigma\in\Sigma_{\Delta}$ and $g\colon|\Delta|\to\mathscr{T}(\Gamma)$ iff all $f^{\#}(t_{i})$ are defined and $i\leq j$ in $\Delta$ implies $f^{\#}(g(i))\leq f^{\#}(g(j))$ in $A$; then $f^{\#}(\sigma(g))=\sigma_{A}(f^{\#}\cdot g)$.
Definition 5.6 ([20, Def. 2.1]). A Lawvere $\mathsf{Pos}$-theory for $\mathcal{V}=\mathsf{Set}$ is a small ordinary category $\mathscr{T}$ together with an ordinary identity-on-objects functor $\iota\colon\mathsf{Pos}_{\mathsf{f}}^{\mathsf{op}}\to\mathscr{T}$ preserving finite limits.
Definition 3.16. A variety of $\Sigma$-algebras is a full subcategory of $\operatorname{\mathop{\mathsf{Alg}}}\Sigma$ specified by a set $\mathcal{E}$ of inequations in context. We denote it by $\operatorname{\mathop{\mathsf{Alg}}}(\Sigma,\mathcal{E})$.\smnotePlease do not delete; it is used all the time.\lsnoteCalling a set of inequations ‘$\mathcal{E}$’ is maybe not very suggestive, or rather suggestive of the wrong thing. How about $\mathcal{I}$ like in Chase’s thesis? Analogously, a variety of coherent $\Sigma$-algebras is a full subcategory of $\operatorname{\mathop{\mathsf{Alg}}}_{\mathsf{c}}\Sigma$ specified by a set of inequations in context.
Definition 2.1. A signature is a functor from ${\mid}\mathsf{Pos}_{\mathsf{f}}{\mid}$ to $\mathsf{Pos}.$ In other words, a signature $\Sigma$ is a collection of posets $\Sigma_{\Gamma}$ of operation symbols in context $\Gamma$ indexed by $\Gamma\in\mathsf{Pos}_{\mathsf{f}}$. A morphism $s\colon\Sigma\to\Sigma^{\prime}$ of signatures, being a natural transformation, is thus just a family of monotone maps $s_{\Gamma}\colon\Sigma_{\Gamma}\to\Sigma_{\Gamma}^{\prime}$ indexed by contexts. We denote by $\mathsf{Sig}=[|\mathsf{Pos}_{\mathsf{f}}|,\mathsf{Pos}]$ the category of signatures and their morphisms.
Definition 3.25. Given a variety $\mathcal{V}$, the left adjoint of $U\colon\mathcal{V}\to\mathsf{Pos}$ assigns to every poset $X$ the free algebra of $\mathcal{V}$ on $X$. The ensuing monad is called the free-algebra monad of the variety and is denoted by $\mathbb{T}_{\mathcal{V}}$.
Definition 3.10. We define terms as usual in universal algebra, ignoring the order structure of arities; we write $\mathscr{T}(\Gamma)$ for the set of $\Sigma$-terms in variables from $\Gamma$. Explicitly, the set $\mathscr{T}(\Gamma)$ of terms is the least set containing $|\Gamma|$ such that given an operation $\sigma$ with arity $\Delta$ and a function $f\colon|\Delta|\to\mathscr{T}(\Gamma)$, we obtain a term $\sigma(f)\in\mathscr{T}(\Gamma)$.
Definition 3.2. A signature in context\lsnoteThis term is not ideal is a set $\Sigma$ of operation symbols each with a prescribed context, its arity. That is, $\Sigma$ is a collection $(\Sigma_{\Gamma})_{\Gamma\in\mathsf{Pos}_{\mathsf{f}}}$ of sets $\Sigma_{\Gamma}$. A $\Sigma$-algebra is a poset $A$ together with, for every $\sigma\in\Sigma_{\Gamma}$, a function $\sigma_{A}\colon\mathsf{Pos}_{0}(\Gamma,A)\rightarrow A.$ That is, $\sigma_{A}$ assigns to every monotone valuation $f\colon\Gamma\rightarrow A$ of the variables in $\Gamma$ an element $\sigma_{A}(f)$ of $A$. The algebra $A$ is called coherent if each $\sigma_{A}$ is monotone, i.e. whenever $f\leq g$ in $\mathsf{Pos}(\Gamma,A)$, then $\sigma_{A}(f)\leq\sigma_{A}(g)$.
Definition 5.1 ([23]). A Lawvere $\mathsf{Pos}$-theory is a small enriched category $\mathscr{T}$ with finite cotensors together with an enriched identity-on-objects functor $\iota\colon\mathsf{Pos}_{\mathsf{f}}^{\mathsf{op}}\to\mathscr{T}$ which preserves finite cotensors.
Definition 3.14. An inequation in context $\Gamma$ is a pair $(s,t)$ of terms in $\mathscr{T}(\Gamma)$, written in the form $\Gamma\vdash s\leq t.$ Furthermore, we denote by $\Gamma\vdash s=t$ the conjunction of the inequations $\Gamma\vdash s\leq t$ and $\Gamma\vdash t\leq s$. A $\Sigma$-algebra satisfies $\Gamma\vdash s\leq t$ if for every monotone function $f\colon\Gamma\to A$, both $f^{\#}(s)$ and $f^{\#}(t)$ are defined and $f^{\#}(s)\leq f^{\#}(t)$.
Definition 2.1. Suppose $W_{1}$, $W_{2}$, and $W_{3}$ are grading-restricted generalized $V$-modules. An intertwining operator of type $\binom{W_{3}}{W_{1}\,W_{2}}$ is a linear map $\displaystyle\mathcal{Y}:W_{1}\otimes W_{2}$ $\displaystyle\rightarrow W_{3}[\log x]\{x\}$ $\displaystyle w_{1}\otimes w_{2}$ $\displaystyle\mapsto\mathcal{Y}(w_{1},x)w_{2}=\sum_{h\in\mathbb{C}}\sum_{k\in% \mathbb{N}}(w_{1})_{h,k}w_{2}\,x^{-h-1}(\log x)^{k}$ which satisfies the following properties: (1) Lower truncation: For any $w_{1}\in W_{1}$, $w_{2}\in W_{2}$, and $h\in\mathbb{C}$, $(w_{1})_{h+n,k}w_{2}=0$ for $n\in\mathbb{Z}$ sufficiently large, independently of $k$. (2) The Jacobi identity: For $v\in V$ and $w_{1}\in W_{1}$, $\displaystyle x_{0}^{-1}\delta\left(\frac{x_{1}-x_{2}}{x_{0}}\right)Y_{W_{3}}(% v,x_{1})\mathcal{Y}(w_{1},x_{2})$ $\displaystyle-x_{0}^{-1}\left(\frac{-x_{2}+x_{1}}{x_{0}}\right)\mathcal{Y}(w_{% 1},x_{2})Y_{W_{2}}(v,x_{1})$ $\displaystyle=x_{1}^{-1}\delta\left(\frac{x_{2}+x_{0}}{x_{1}}\right)\mathcal{Y% }(Y_{W_{1}}(v,x_{0})w_{1},x_{2}).$ (3) The $L_{-1}$-derivative property: For $w_{1}\in W_{1}$, $\mathcal{Y}(L_{-1}w_{1},x)=\dfrac{d}{dx}\mathcal{Y}(w_{1},x).$
Definition 2.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category of grading-restricted generalized $V$-modules containing $W_{1}$ and $W_{2}$. A tensor product of $W_{1}$ and $W_{2}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ is a pair $(W_{1}\boxtimes W_{2},\mathcal{Y}_{\boxtimes})$, with $W_{1}\boxtimes W_{2}$ a module in $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{Y}_{\boxtimes}$ an intertwining operator of type $\binom{W_{1}\boxtimes W_{2}}{W_{1}\,W_{2}}$, which satisfies the following universal property: For any module $W_{3}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ and intertwining operator $\mathcal{Y}$ of type $\binom{W_{3}}{W_{1}\,W_{2}}$, there is a unique $V$-module homomorphism $f:W_{1}\boxtimes W_{2}\rightarrow W_{3}$ such that $\mathcal{Y}=f\circ\mathcal{Y}_{\boxtimes}$.
Definition 5.1. The category $\mathcal{O}_{c}^{0}$ is the Müger centralizer of $\operatorname{Rep}SO(3,\mathbb{R})$ in $\mathcal{O}_{c}$, that is, $\mathcal{O}_{c}^{0}\subseteq\mathcal{O}_{c}$ is the full subcategory whose objects $\mathcal{W}$ satisfy $\mathcal{R}_{\mathcal{L}_{2n+1,1},\mathcal{W}}\circ\mathcal{R}_{\mathcal{W},% \mathcal{L}_{2n+1,1}}=\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{W}\boxtimes\mathcal{L}_{2n+1,1}}$ for all $n\in\mathbb{N}$.
Definition A.6 (Geodesic filtration). Consider a filtration $X_{0}\to X_{1}\to\dots\to X_{n}.$ We inductively define what it means for such a filtration to be geodesic. All filtrations for $n=0$ and $1$ are geodesic. For $n\geq 2$, the filtration is geodesic if (1) the filtration $X_{1}\to\dots\to X_{n}$ is geodesic, and (2) the map $\operatorname{Cone}(X_{1}\to X_{n})\to\operatorname{Cone}(X_{0}\to X_{1})[1]$ is rectifiable.
Definition 6.11 (Gromov coordinates). Let $\tau$ be a stability condition of type A. For each integer $i\in\mathbb{Z}$, let $x_{i}(\tau)$ be the rational number defined as follows: $x_{i}(\tau)=\frac{m_{\tau}(P_{i-1})+m_{\tau}(P_{i+1})-2m_{\tau}(P_{i})}{2}.$ We call the numbers $(x_{i}(\tau))$ the Gromov coordinates of $\tau$.
Definition A.1 (Rectifiable map). We say that a map $B\to A[1]$ is rectifiable if for every $\alpha\in\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}$, the induced map $B_{>\alpha}\to A_{\leq\alpha}[1]$ vanishes.
Definition 4.2. Suppose $\Theta$ is a $\tau$-mass automaton. We say that $\Theta$ is degenerating if there exists a finite set $T$ of non-degenerate triangles such that for every $g\in G$, either $\tau$ and $g^{-1}\tau$ have the same stable objects or $g=\sigma(e)$ for some arrow $e$ in $\Theta$ that degenerates a triangle in $T$.
Definition 3.1. A $\tau$-HN automaton consists of a $G$-automaton $\Theta$ along with the following additional data: (1) a sub $\Theta$-set $S\subset\operatorname{ob}\mathcal{C}$, (2) a $\Theta$-representation $M$ and an $\Theta$-equivariant map $i\colon S\to M$, (3) for every state $v$, a linear map $HN_{v}\colon M(v)\to\mathbb{Z}^{\Sigma}$. The data is required to satisfy the following for every $s\in S(v)$: $HN_{\tau}(s)=HN_{v}(i(s)).$ A $\tau$-mass automaton is analogous, with $HN_{v}$ replaced by $m_{v}\colon M(v)\to\mathbb{R}$ that satisfies $m_{\tau}(s)=m_{v}(i(s)).$
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category. For $n\geq 1$, we define an $n$-dimensional stable independence notion on $\mathcal{K}$, $\Gamma$, and its induced category, $\mathcal{K}^{\Gamma}$, proceeding by induction on $n$: • We say that $\Gamma$ is a $1$-dimensional stable independence notion on $\mathcal{K}$ just in case it is the collection of all morphisms in $\mathcal{K}$. In this case, we define $\mathcal{K}^{\Gamma}=\mathcal{K}$. • An $(n+1)$-dimensional stable independence notion on $\mathcal{K}$ consists of a pair $(\Gamma_{n},\Gamma)$, where – $\Gamma_{n}$ is an $n$-dimensional stable independence notion on $\mathcal{K}$, and – $\Gamma$ is a stable independence notion on $\mathcal{K}^{\Gamma_{n}}$, in the sense of Definition 2.2(3). • Given an $(n+1)$-dimensional stable independence notion $\Gamma_{n+1}=(\Gamma_{n},\Gamma)$ on $\mathcal{K}$, we define $\mathcal{K}^{\Gamma_{n+1}}$ to be the category $(\mathcal{K}^{\Gamma_{n}})^{\Gamma}$, whose objects are morphisms of $\mathcal{K}^{\Gamma_{n}}$ and whose morphisms are the $\Gamma$-independent squares. Note that this is precisely $(\mathcal{K}^{\Gamma_{n}})_{\downarrow}$ with $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits=\Gamma$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category, and $\mathcal{M}$ a class of morphisms in $\mathcal{K}$. (1) We say that $\mathcal{M}$ is almost nice if it is satisfies the following conditions: (a) $\mathcal{M}$ is normal: it contains all isomorphisms in $\mathcal{K}$ and is closed under composition ([LRV19a, 3.1]). (b) $\mathcal{M}$ is coherent: whenever $f$ and $g$ are composable morphisms with $gf\in\mathcal{M}$ and $g\in\mathcal{M}$, then $f\in\mathcal{M}$ as well ([LRV19a, 3.3]). (c) $\mathcal{M}$ is a coclan: the pushout of any two morphisms, at least one of which is in $\mathcal{M}$, exists, and $\mathcal{M}$ is closed under pushouts ([LRV19a, 4.1(1)]). Incidentally, we say that $\mathcal{M}$ is nice if it is also closed under retracts. (2) We say that $\mathcal{M}$ is $\lambda$-continuous, $\lambda$ an infinite regular cardinal, if $\mathcal{K}$ has $\lambda$-directed colimits, and $\mathcal{M}$ is closed under $\lambda$-directed colimits in $\mathcal{K}$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category, and $\mathcal{M}$ a class of morphisms in $\mathcal{K}$. An $\mathcal{M}$-effective square is a commutative square $\xymatrix{B\ar[r]^{h}&D\\ A\ar[u]^{f}\ar[r]_{g}&C\ar[u]_{k}}$ such that the pushout $P$ of $f$ and $g$ exists, and the induced morphism $P\to D$ is in $\mathcal{M}$.
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ be an independence notion on category $\mathcal{K}$, satisfying the existence and transitivity properties. We say that $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ is $\lambda$-continuous if $\mathcal{K}_{\downarrow}$ is closed in $\mathcal{K}^{2}$ under $\lambda$-directed colimits.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category. (1) We define an independence notion (or independence relation) on $\mathcal{K}$ as a class $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ of commutatives squares (called $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$-independent, or simply independent) such that, for any commutative diagram $\xymatrix{&&E\\ B\ar[r]\ar@/^{/}[rru]&D\ar[ur]&\\ A\ar[r]\ar[u]&C\ar[u]\ar@/_{/}[uur]&}$ the square spanning $A$, $B$, $C$, and $D$ is independent if and only if the square spanning $A$, $B$, $C$, and $E$ is independent. (2) We say that an independence notion on $\mathcal{K}$ is weakly stable if it satisfies the following conditions: (a) Symmetry: $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ is closed under reflection across the diagonal from bottom left to top right. (b) Transitivity: $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ is closed under vertical and horizontal composition of squares. (c) Existence: Any span $B\leftarrow A\to C$ can be completed to a $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$-independent square. (d) Uniqueness: Any two completions of a span $B\leftarrow A\to C$ to $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$-independent squares are equivalent up to amalgamation, in the sense of the diagram in (1) above.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ be an independence notion on category $\mathcal{K}$, satisfying the existence and transitivity properties. (1) We denote by $\mathcal{K}_{\downarrow}$ the subcategory of the arrow category $\mathcal{K}^{2}$ whose objects are $\mathcal{K}$-morphisms, and whose morphisms are $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$-independent squares. (Our assumption on $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ in the preamble of this definition is needed only to ensure that $\mathcal{K}_{\downarrow}$ does indeed form a category.) (2) We say that $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ is $\lambda$-accessible, $\lambda$ an infinite regular cardinal, if the category $\mathcal{K}_{\downarrow}$ is $\lambda$-accessible. We say that $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ is accessible if it is $\lambda$-accessible for some $\lambda$. (3) We say that $\mathop{\hbox{\lower 2.0pt\hbox to 7.499886pt{\hfil\vrule width 0.3pt depth -2% .0pt height 10.0pt\hfil}\lower 2.0pt\hbox{$\textstyle\smile$}}}\limits$ is a stable independence notion it if is weakly stable and accessible.
Definition 2.4. We say that a functor $F:\mathcal{L}\to\mathcal{K}$ is cofinal if for any $K\in\mathcal{K}$, and any finite sequence $\left(FL_{i}\xrightarrow{f_{i}}K\right)_{i\in I}$, there exists $L\in\mathcal{L}$, $K\xrightarrow{g}FL$ and $\left(FL_{i}\xrightarrow{Fg_{i}}FL\right)_{i\in I}$ such that $Fg_{i}=f_{i}\cdot g$ for all $i\in I$. We say that a subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ of a category $\mathcal{K}$ is cofinal if the inclusion is cofinal.
Definition 4.2. We say that a category $\mathcal{K}$ is excellent if for all $n\geq 1$, $\mathcal{K}$ has an $n$-dimensional stable independence notion $\Gamma_{n}$ so that $\mathcal{K}^{\Gamma_{n}}$ has directed colimits.
Definition 1.4.4. For a $k$-linear Grothendieck topology $\mathcal{T}$ on $\mathbf{a}$, a presheaf $F\in\mathsf{PSh}\mathbf{a}$ is a $\mathcal{T}$-sheaf if for every $A\in\mathbf{a}$ and $R\in\mathcal{T}(A)$, the morphism induced from $R\hookrightarrow\mathbf{a}(-,A)$ $F(A)\simeq\mathrm{Nat}(\mathbf{a}(-,A),F)\to\mathrm{Nat}(R,F)$ is an isomorphism. The full subcategory of $\mathsf{PSh}\mathbf{a}$ of $\mathcal{T}$-sheaves is denoted by $\mathsf{Sh}(\mathbf{a},\mathcal{T})$.
Definition 3.2.1. A topology $\mathcal{T}$ is subcanonical if every representable presheaf is a $\mathcal{T}$-sheaf.
Definition 2.2.1. A $k$-linear Grothendieck pretopology on $\mathbf{a}$ is a class $\mathcal{S}$ of sequences of the form (4) such that (PTa) and (PTb) are satisfied: (PTa) For each $q:\amalg_{\beta}Y_{\beta}\to X$ in $\mathcal{C}o(\mathcal{S})$ and morphism $f:A\to X$, there exists $q^{\prime}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{C}o}_{A}(\mathcal{S})$ which admits a (formal) commutative diagram $\xymatrix{\amalg_{\beta}Y_{\beta}\ar[rr]^{q}&&X\\ \amalg_{\delta}C_{\delta}\ar@{-->}[rr]^{q^{\prime}}\ar@{-->}[u]^{f^{\prime}}&&% A\ar[u]^{f}.}$ (PTb) For every sequence (4) in $\mathcal{S}$ and $f:A\to\amalg_{\beta}Y_{\beta}$ with $q\circ f=0$, there exists $q^{\prime}\in\widetilde{\mathcal{C}o}_{A}(\mathcal{S})$ which admits a (formal) commutative diagram $\xymatrix{\amalg_{\gamma}Z_{\gamma}\ar[r]^{p}&\amalg_{\beta}Y_{\beta}\ar[r]^{q% }&X\\ \amalg_{\alpha}B_{\alpha}\ar@{-->}[r]^{q^{\prime}}\ar@{-->}[u]^{f^{\prime}}&A% \ar[u]^{f}\ar@{-}[ru]_{0}.}$
Definition 3.1.1. A Grothendieck topology $\mathcal{T}$ is $\kappa$-noetherian if for every $X\in\mathbf{a}$, the object $\mathtt{Z}(X)$ is $\kappa$-compact in $\mathsf{Sh}(\mathbf{a},\mathcal{T})$.
Definition 1.4.2. A $k$-linear Grothendieck topology is a covering system $\mathcal{T}$ on $\mathbf{a}$ such that for every $A\in\mathbf{a}$: (T1) We have $\mathbf{a}(-,A)\in\mathcal{T}(A)$; (T2) For $R\in\mathcal{T}(A)$ and a morphism $f:B\to A$ in $\mathbf{a}$, we have $f^{-1}R\in\mathcal{T}(B)$; (T3) For a sieve $S$ on $A$ and $R\in\mathcal{T}(A)$ such that for every $B\in\mathbf{a}$ and $f\in R(B)\subset\mathbf{a}(B,A)$ we have $f^{-1}S\in\mathcal{T}(B)$, it follows that $S\in\mathcal{T}(A)$.
Definition 1.5.1. A Grothendieck pretopology on a category $\mathbf{c}$ is an assignment to each $U\in\mathbf{c}$ of a collection of sets of morphisms $\{U_{i}\to U\}$, called coverings of $U$, such that: (pt0) If $\{U_{i}\to U\}$ is a covering and $f:V\to U$ any morphism, then all $U_{i}\times_{U}V$ exist. (pt1) If $V\to U$ is an isomorphism, then $\{V\to U\}$ is a covering. (pt2) If $\{U_{i}\to U\}$ is a covering and $f:V\to U$ any morphism in $\mathbf{c}$, then $\{U_{i}\times_{U}V\to V\}$ is a covering. (pt3) If $\{U_{i}\to U\}$ and $\{V_{ij}\to U_{i}\}$ are coverings, then $\{V_{ij}\to U_{i}\to V\}$ is a covering.
Definition 2.5. An ideal $\mathscr{P}$ of a Tambara functor ${T}$ is prime if for any pair of ideals $\mathscr{I}$ and $\mathscr{J}$, $\mathscr{I}\mathscr{J}\subseteq\mathscr{P}\implies\mathscr{I}\subseteq\mathscr% {P}\text{ or }\mathscr{J}\subseteq\mathscr{P},$ where the product of ideals is defined as $\mathscr{I}\mathscr{J}(X)=\{f_{+}(ab)\mid f\in G\mathbf{Fin}(A,X)\text{for % some }A,\;a\in\mathscr{I}(A),\;b\in\mathscr{J}(A)\}.$
Definition 3.1. Let $G$ be a finite group and $\underline{A}_{G}$ the Burnside Tambara functor on $G$. Let $C$ be a subgroup of $G$ and $p$ a prime or zero. For each $H\leq G$ define $\mathfrak{p}_{C,p}(G/H)=\bigcap_{\begin{subarray}{c}I\leq H\\ I\preccurlyeq_{G}C\end{subarray}}\ker(\varphi_{H,p}^{I})$ where $I\preccurlyeq_{G}C$ means that there exists some $g\in G$ such that $I^{g}\leq C$.
Definition 2.2. A Tambara functor $T$ on a profinite group $G$ is completely specified by a ring $T(G/H)$ for all open $H\leq G$ and the following maps for all open subgroups $L\leq H\leq G$: (1) Restriction ${\rm res}_{L}^{H}:=q^{*}$ (2) Transfer ${\rm tr}_{L}^{H}:=q_{+}$ (3) Norm ${\rm N}_{L}^{H}:=q_{\boldsymbol{\cdot}}$ (4) Conjugation $c_{g,H}:=(c_{g})^{*}$ where $q\colon G/K\rightarrow G/H$ is the quotient map and $c_{g}\colon G/H^{g}\rightarrow G/H$ is conjugation-by-$g$ with $H^{g}=g^{-1}Hg$. These maps must satisfy a number of compatibility conditions as specified M. Hill and K. Mazur in [5].
Definition 2.8. The Burnside ring of a group $G$ is the Grothendieck construction on the semi-ring of finite $G$-sets, denoted $A(G)$. That is, $A(G)$ is the ring of formal differences of isomorphism classes of finite $G$-sets, with addition given by disjoint union and multiplication given by Cartesian product.
Definition 3.2. Let $T$ be a Tambara functor on a group $G$ and let $f=\{f_{H}\}_{H\leq G}$ be a collection of injective ring homomorphisms $f\colon T(G/H)\rightarrow R_{H}$ for some rings $R_{H}$. For each $H\leq G$ define $T^{f}(G/H)={\rm im}(f_{H})$. Furthermore for each $H\leq K\leq G$ and $g\in G$ define maps $\displaystyle{\rm res}_{H}^{K}$ $\displaystyle=f_{H}\circ{\rm res}_{H}^{K}\circ f_{K}^{-1}$ $\displaystyle{\rm tr}_{H}^{K}$ $\displaystyle=f_{K}\circ{\rm tr}_{H}^{K}\circ f_{H}^{-1}$ $\displaystyle{\rm N}_{H}^{K}$ $\displaystyle=f_{K}\circ{\rm N}_{H}^{K}\circ f_{H}^{-1}$ $\displaystyle c_{g,H}$ $\displaystyle=f_{H^{g}}\circ c_{g,H}\circ f^{-1}_{H}$ where res, tr, N, and $c$ on the right refer to the restriction, transfer, norm and conjugation maps in $\underline{T}$.
Definition 2.4. An ideal $\mathscr{I}$ of $T$ consists of a collection of standard ring-theoretic ideals $\mathscr{I}(G/H)\subseteq T(G/H)$ for each open $H\leq G$, such that for all open subgroups $K\leq H$ (1) ${\rm res}_{K}^{H}(\mathscr{I}(G/H))\subseteq\mathscr{I}(G/K)$, (2) ${\rm tr}_{K}^{H}(\mathscr{I}(G/K))\subseteq\mathscr{I}(G/H)$, (3) ${\rm N}_{K}^{H}(\mathscr{I}(G/K))\subseteq\mathscr{I}(G/H)+{\rm N}_{K}^{H}(0)$, (4) $c_{g,H}(\mathscr{I}(G/H))\subseteq\mathscr{I}(G/H^{g})$. Let $\mathcal{G}\subseteq T$, where we consider $T$ as the disjoint union of the rings $T(X)$ over finite $G$-sets $X$. The ideal generated by $\mathcal{G}$ is the intersection of all ideals of $T$ containing $\mathcal{G}$, denoted $(\!(\mathcal{G})\!)$. If $\mathcal{G}=\{a_{1},\dots,a_{n}\}$ is finite, then we write $(\!(\mathcal{G})\!)=(\!(a_{1},\dots,a_{n})\!)$.
Definition 2.10. For any subgroup $H\leq G$ and $p$ prime, let $O^{p}(H)$ denote the unique normal $p$-perfect subgroup such that the quotient $H/O^{p}(H)$ is a $p$-group. That is, $O^{p}(H)=\bigcap I,$ where the intersection is over all $I\trianglelefteq H$ such that $|H:I|=p^{n}$ for some $n\in\mathbb{N}$.
Definition 2.7. The spectrum of a Tambara functor $T$, denoted $\operatorname{Spec}(T)$, is the collection of all prime ideals $\mathscr{P}$ of $T$. The topology on $\operatorname{Spec}(T)$ is given by the collection of closed sets of the form $V(\mathscr{I})=\{\mathscr{P}\in\operatorname{Spec}(T)\mid\mathscr{I}\subseteq% \mathscr{P}\}$ for all ideals $\mathscr{I}$ of $T$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\varphi=\{\varphi_{H}\}_{H\leq G}$, where $\varphi_{H}$ is as defined in Equation 2.2. Then by Theorem 3.1, $\underline{A}_{G}^{\varphi}$ is a Tambara functor isomorphic to $\underline{A}_{G}$. We call the ring $\underline{A}_{G}^{\varphi}(G/G)$ the ghost ring of $G$. Given $C\leq G$ and $p$ a prime or zero define $\mathscr{K}_{C,p}$ by $\mathscr{K}_{C,p}(G/H)=\left(\prod_{I\leq H}\chi_{C,p}(I)\right)\cap\underline% {A}_{G}^{\varphi}(G/H)$ where $\chi_{C,p}(I)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}(p)&I\preccurlyeq_{G}C\\ \mathbb{Z}&{\rm otherwise.}\end{array}\right.$
Definition 2.11 (The Burnside Tambara functor). For each open $H\leq G$, set $\underline{A}_{G}(G/H)=A(H)$. For open subgroups $K\leq H\leq G$, $g\in G$, $Y\in\underline{A}_{G}(G/H)$, and $X\in\underline{A}_{G}(G/L)$, we define the Tambara structure maps, $\displaystyle{\rm res}_{K}^{H}\colon\underline{A}_{G}(G/H)$ $\displaystyle\longrightarrow\underline{A}_{G}(G/K)$ $\displaystyle Y$ $\displaystyle\longmapsto Y\text{ with restricted $K$-action,}$ $\displaystyle{\rm tr}_{K}^{H}\colon\underline{A}_{G}(G/K)$ $\displaystyle\longrightarrow\underline{A}_{G}(G/H)$ $\displaystyle X$ $\displaystyle\longmapsto H\times_{K}X,$ $\displaystyle{\rm N}_{K}^{H}\colon\underline{A}_{G}(G/K)$ $\displaystyle\longrightarrow\underline{A}_{G}(G/H)$ $\displaystyle X$ $\displaystyle\longmapsto{\rm Map}_{K}(H,X),$ $\displaystyle c_{g,H}\colon\underline{A}_{G}(G/H)$ $\displaystyle\longrightarrow\underline{A}_{G}(G/H^{g})$ $\displaystyle X$ $\displaystyle\longmapsto X^{g}.$ When $G$ is Abelian, conjugation is trivial. These maps turn $\underline{A}_{G}$ into the initial $G$-Tambara functor (cf. [8, 9]). We will denote $\underline{A}_{G}$ by merely $\underline{A}$ when the group is obvious from context.
Definition 5.1. The Möbius function of a finite poset is defined by $\mu(a,b)=\begin{cases}0&a\not\leq b,\\ 1&a=b,\\ -\sum_{x\leq b}\mu(a,x)&\text{otherwise.}\end{cases}$ The Möbius function of a finite group $G$ is defined as the Möbius function of the poset of subgroups of $G$ partially ordered by inclusion. If $G$ is a cyclic group and $H\leq K\leq G$, then $\mu(H,K)=\mu(|K:H|),$ where the $\mu$ on the right side of the equality is the standard Möbius function from number theory.
Definition 2.9. Given a prime (or zero) $p$, let $\varphi_{G,p}^{H}\colon A(G)\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$ denote the composition of $\varphi_{G}^{H}$ and the usual quotient map $\mathbb{Z}\rightarrow\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$.
